Yes, the JupyterLab `IFrame` widget from `@jupyterlab/ui-components` sets the `sandbox` attribute by default for security reasons. To completely remove it, you'll need to override its behavior.

### Solution: Override the `sandbox` Attribute
JupyterLab‚Äôs `IFrame` widget automatically applies a sandbox, but you can manually remove it after creating the iframe element.

#### Example: Creating an `IFrame` without Sandbox in a JupyterLab Extension
```typescript
import { IFrame } from '@jupyterlab/ui-components';
import { Widget } from '@lumino/widgets';

// Create the iframe widget
const iframe = new IFrame();
iframe.url = 'https://your-trusted-origin.com';
iframe.node.style.width = '100%';
iframe.node.style.height = '100vh';

// Remove the sandbox attribute
iframe.node.removeAttribute('sandbox');

// Add iframe to a parent widget or JupyterLab panel
const panel = new Widget();
panel.node.appendChild(iframe.node);
```

### Alternative: Directly Create a Native `<iframe>`
If overriding `sandbox` within JupyterLab‚Äôs `IFrame` still causes issues, you can directly create an `<iframe>` element and insert it into a Lumino `Widget`:

```typescript
import { Widget } from '@lumino/widgets';

// Create a plain iframe
const iframe = document.createElement('iframe');
iframe.src = 'https://your-trusted-origin.com';
iframe.style.width = '100%';
iframe.style.height = '100vh';

// DO NOT set sandbox, ensuring all protections are removed
// iframe.sandbox = 'allow-same-origin allow-scripts'; // Not needed

// Wrap it in a Lumino widget
const panel = new Widget();
panel.node.appendChild(iframe);
```

### Why This Works:
- The `IFrame` widget in JupyterLab enforces `sandbox` by default for security.
- Calling `removeAttribute('sandbox')` ensures it's fully removed.
- If `IFrame` still applies protections, using a plain `<iframe>` inside a Lumino `Widget` bypasses JupyterLab‚Äôs restrictions.

